f the U.S. Navy and conducted scores of interviews with Vietnam veterans - both black and white - and other military personnel to reveal the full extent of racial unrest in the Navy during the Vietnam War era, as well as the Navy’s attempts to control it. During the second half of the Vietnam War, the Navy witnessed some of the worst incidents of racial strife ever experienced by the American military. Sherwood introduces us to fierce encounters on American warships and bases, ranging from sit-down strikes to major race riots.The Navy’s journey from a state of racial polarization to one of relative harmony was not an easy one, and Black Sailor, White Navy focuses on the most turbulent point in this road: the Vietnam War era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American sailorsxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American sailorsxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aProtest movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xAfrican Americans. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh  aNavy.  aNavys.  aSherwood.  aVietnam.  aattempts.  acontrol.  aduring.  aera.  aextent.  afull.  aracial.  areveals.  aunrest.  awell.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474036140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814786789.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814786789/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL 